  "prompt": "What is the function of a mitochondria in a cell?",
  "response": "Mitochondria are often referred to as the \"powerhouses\" of the cell because their primary function is to produce energy in the form of ATP (adenosine triphosphate) through cellular respiration. Here are the key functions of mitochondria:\n\n1. Energy Production\n- Convert nutrients into usable cellular energy (ATP)\n- Perform cellular respiration through the electron transport chain\n- Generate about 90% of a cell's energy requirements\n\n2. Metabolic Processes\n- Regulate cellular metabolism\n- Participate in fat, protein, and carbohydrate metabolism\n- Help in synthesizing certain hormones and chemicals\n\n3. Cellular Signaling\n- Play a role in cell communication\n- Involved in cell growth and cell death (apoptosis)\n\n4. Calcium Storage\n- Store and regulate calcium ions\n- Help control calcium signaling in cells\n\n5. Heat Generation\n- Produce heat through metabolic processes\n- Important for maintaining body temperature\n\n6. Cell Survival\n- Protect cells from oxidative stress\n- Help in maintaining cellular health and preventing damage\n\nMitochondria are unique because they have their own DNA and can replicate independently within the cell, making them crucial for cellular function and survival.",
